{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01FpU9cJbJwaXoyCMuFKeMDe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01P85XjNGsxtbjd2cYXxvFsS","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-2-2-observability-hook-enforcement && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p 'You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user'\"'\"'s perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product'\"'\"'s documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\nThere are 3 ACs to verify:\n1. Given static coverage target is 80%, When current static coverage is 72%, Then pre-commit hook blocks with message showing current vs target.\n2. Given both static and runtime coverage pass targets, When commit is attempted, Then hook allows it.\n3. Given hook blocks, When the message is displayed, Then it includes specific files/functions missing logging and how to fix.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n\nThe container has: `codeharness`, `claude`, `curl`, `jq`, `node`, `npm`.\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '\"'\"'<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\"'\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container):\n- VictoriaLogs: http://localhost:9428\n- VictoriaMetrics: http://localhost:8428\n- VictoriaTraces: http://localhost:16686\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command, query:\n```\ncurl '\"'\"'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\"'\"'\n```\n\nIf zero log entries, include: `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Verification Strategy for This Story\n\nThis story is about the `codeharness observability-gate` CLI command and its integration with the pre-commit hook. To verify:\n\n**AC 1 (block when below target):**\n1. Create a sprint-state.json inside the container with static coverage at 72% and target at 80%\n2. Run `codeharness observability-gate` and verify it exits non-zero with a message showing 72% vs 80%\n3. Also test the hook script directly by setting up a minimal git repo and running the hook\n\n**AC 2 (allow when passing):**\n1. Create a sprint-state.json with static at 85% (above 80% target)\n2. Run `codeharness observability-gate` and verify it exits 0\n\n**AC 3 (gap details in block message):**\n1. Create a sprint-state.json with coverage below target AND gaps array\n2. Run `codeharness observability-gate --json` and verify the output includes gap details (file, line, description)\n3. Verify the human-readable output includes fix suggestions\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/2-2-observability-hook-enforcement-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\nIMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages. Never use bare fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Do NOT attempt to access source code — there is no src/ directory.\n3. Report REAL failures — never fabricate evidence.\n4. Every AC needs functional evidence — reading docs alone is not evidence.\n5. Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.\n6. [ESCALATE] is ONLY for things genuinely impossible to automate.\n7. Never switch to unit-testable verification.' 2>&1","description":"Run black-box verifier session","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":163,"cache_read_input_tokens":58664,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":163},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7a66acd-0cc1-40de-a592-d59e75273c0b","uuid":"00109688-13fd-4b21-b798-d86117620b41"}
